A Republican strategy to oppose Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justify their policies by the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, affirming that election fraud in the United States is less common than the number of people killed by lightning strikes.
Republican lawyers have, by the way, only recorded 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures undermine partly the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the federal states are responsible for holding elections in each state.
In this sense, since 2009, the majority of American governments have enacted new laws that make it more difficult to register or vote.
This phenomenon gained momentum after the November 2010 elections, in which 675 new Republican representatives were registered in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were introduced in 2011 alone that restrict the exercise of voting rights in 41 states.
The new election laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also reduce the time limits for early voting, invalidate the right to register as a voter on Election Day and deny citizens the right to vote in respect of which a court order is made.
Before the 2006 election, no US state required voters to show a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a claim.
The Supreme Court of the United States upheld the constitutionality of Indiana's law in 2008.
The Republican authorities are rushing to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have promoted bills in 34 states that force voters to show a photo ID.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, US citizens do not have a universal identification card like the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of US citizens, i.e. 21 million eligible voters, do not have a photo ID issued by a government agency in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a card.
However, often more than a hundred dollars are paid to obtain the required ID.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people with incomes below $35,000, 18% of citizens over the age of 65, and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
This goes further.
Students who are considered voters who are increasingly voting for democratic candidates are not allowed to use their school-issued photo ID in several states.
On the other hand, the same States allow members of fishing or hunting associations who vote more for the Republican side to use the election cards issued by these associations.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of citizenship for voting.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove their U.S. citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Spanish vote.
Because it's obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in eight states in 2011 promoted laws that abolished voter registration on Election Day.
In addition, you have restricted the right of individuals and groups to assist those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, the voter registration campaigns in the 2004 general elections helped register about 10 million citizens.
The measures adopted since 2009 have led to a 17% decrease in the proportion of newcomers registered in 2010 compared with 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in five other states have passed laws aimed at shortening the time for early voting.
For example, in the 2008 Florida general election, 33% of voters who voted in advance were African-American, even though they made up only 13% of the state's electorate.
The same is true of the Hispanic population.
The latter accounted for only 11% of the electorate, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, whites, who represented 76% of the electorate, made up only 46% of those who voted in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have been vigorously opposed to legislation restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by the vetoes of the Democratic governors.
The U.S. Attorney General has intervened to expose the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote.
Democratic critics criticize the party-political nature of the laws passed and see as a clear objective to influence the results in the states that have decided for 2012.
A 2011 report from the Brennan Center shows that the states that passed these laws received 171 of the 270 votes needed in the Electoral College to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these changes to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is certain: these new rules will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures undermine partly the democratic system of the United States.
