The Higgs boson is analyzed
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson caused some alarm last summer, and for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it's the last particle whose existence is predicted by the standard model -- our best or least false explanation of the nature and behavior of matter -- but not yet empirically observed.
But physicists aren't entirely sure it's actually the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it's very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics conference in Kyoto, but there is still no data to be completely certain about it.
So let's assume it's actually the Higgs, because there's only a slight risk of being wrong, and let's see what it's all about.
There is a law in this world that is inevitable, and it means that two objects cannot be present at the same time in the same place.
It is not possible to break this rule - and do not try too hard, as you will hurt yourself.
Because even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that there is a law of this sort for it too: the Paulie exclusion principle, which says that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state", and that "state" is largely made up of some of their properties.
Based on this, physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner are the good citizens, known as Fermions, who respectfully obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the bosons are moving, an evil gang of anarchists who have nothing sacred -- certainly not this principle, which means they can actually be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons, according to the Berkeley Laboratories' website The Particle Adventure, are divided into two groups (which is absolutely amazing, by the way): the mesons, which we won't be treating here, and the "particles of force" through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would be related in some way.
But it must be emphasized here that these bosons are not all as exotic creatures as you might think.
If you can read this chronicle, it's only because of a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon, or "light particle", which is the "boss" of the electromagnetic force.
When a particle accelerates or changes direction with an electric charge, the electromagnetic field is "distorted" at that exact location, much like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disturbance" produces an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of force".
Stable field
The same goes for the Higgs boson, except that another field, the Higgs field, has to be disturbed in order for that boson to show up.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the agent must reach very high energies, somewhat comparable to a frozen pond whose surface could only be scratched by a very large rock.
So we need a huge particle accelerator like CERN -- the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a radius of 27 kilometers! -- to reach this kind of energy.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others don't - for example, a sheet of paper would never hold onto the refrigerator by itself.
And not all particles interact with the Higgs field equally: those that do have mass, while the others (like the photon, by the way) have no mass.
What is the use of all this research, Mrs Plamondon asks?
For science, they are used to verify the standard model (SM) and also allow physicists to accurately examine any discrepancies between the observations and predictions of SM.
By the way, there are many physicists who are eager to find such deviations, since the slightest difference could open a door to "new physics" and plug some holes in the model.
It must be said that the latter has still great flaws, since it offers no explanation for gravity (up!) and the dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter of the universe (again ups!).
However, no such discrepancies have been found at CERN so far.
Effects
The impact of these studies on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there is none.
By the way, in the early '60s, the pioneers of laser at Bell Labs had no idea that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who himself developed the first permanent laser (the first ones were pulsed) in 1962 - has already told us that the laser was initially considered more of a "laboratory plaything".
Imagine that you...
In addition, applications can also arise from all the instruments surrounding research.
For example, in 1969, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor while working in optics.
Although not the original purpose, this sensor is now used by all digital cameras worldwide as an eye, and it won him the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
Of course, this doesn't mean that the LHC's activities will inevitably change our lives, but it does mean that you really can never know...
Palliative care is the best way to die...
With its committee on "Death with Dignity", Quebec recently discussed the delicate question of the end of life.
The debate must resume shortly, although a draft law is being prepared.
