Le Devoir has tried to look at this more closely.
A few weeks ago Mr L. lived alone in his apartment in the Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that consumed him had given him a two-year deadline.
"They gave me five years to live, I made it seven", he said halfheartedly, lying in his bed in the Victor-Gadbois home for palliative care in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for it", he says.
The disease is doing its job: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table before a delicious lunch, he resigns to be helped with the meal.
He even smiles and talks to the strangers around him, bringing him his medicine, and offering him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is that my diarrhea be cured, as this is humiliating", he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this disease.
"In the course of our lives, we learn that a man peees while standing", says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at Victor-Gadbois Home.
For some people, going back to childhood is an unacceptable humiliation.
"It depends on the person's ability to take a step back", he notes.
Because according to several people working in palliative care, major events are taking place amid these setbacks.
The patients who are admitted to Victor Gadbois' palliative care home all have cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, they are no longer overwhelmed by the doctors and nurses who care for them with so-called "healing" care.
For Mrs. A., 89, the worst fear is to die "consciously and by suffocation".
But the disease really got me to know my children.
"I have good children", she adds.
"I have no wishes in life", she says before accepting a mask to help her breathe.
She is still waiting for her son, who is coming from Italy, to visit her for the last time in the coming days.
The Victor-Gadbois Home offers a group of volunteers to help with physical care and food intake.
Palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make dying more pleasant.
In Quebec, for every 11,700 inhabitants, there is a palliative care bed.
That's very little considering that one day we're all going to die.
Here life is continued under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors at the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional, and spiritual comfort.
The dying person is given oral care with brandy or Pepsi, as desired.
Diabetics no longer have to control their blood sugar.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died in the course of the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help family members and patients alike", reports Nathalie Savard, director of nursing.
Victor Gadbois' home is not a day like any other.
Alongside a 93-year-old man enjoying the last family gathering in the yard, well supported by his pillows while he is honored, a 36-year-old young man, surrounded by his parents, wife and two young children, tragically dies after trying his best to survive.
"For six months, three to five beds have been occupied by cancer patients under 45", says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients admitted to Victor Gadbois' home come from their home, 47% from the hospital.
Problems of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, which is care designed to alleviate the suffering of patients who have reached the end of their lives, whether at home, in a hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, like the Victor Gadbois Home and the Home Palliative Care Society in Greater Montreal, are more or less exclusively dedicated to caring for cancer patients.
It is precisely this large inadequacy in Quebec's health care that causes several palliative care doctors to face the adoption of a law regulating assisted dying and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto has been circulating, signed by prominent figures in palliative care such as Dr Balfour Mount and Dr Bernard Lapointe, to express their opposition to such an initiative.
Dr. Christiane Martel says that Quebec's health system is not sufficiently efficient to ensure that everyone is entitled to high-quality palliative care before accepting the transition to assisted dying.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who had been in the emergency room for 14 days in great pain without any relief measures being taken.
I'm afraid the patients are dying because they don't get adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients, despite the worst prognosis, until the last day.
Hélène Richard's chances of survival were already minimal when she stopped a difficult chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist I was going to stop treatment, she replied that she regretted that I had given up the fight, she said.
But she told me I was done!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the nurses for not granting their wishes after their pain has been relieved by a palliative care team.
But it must be made clear that palliative care is not omnipotent in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care at the Montreal Home Palliative Care Society, 8% of patients do not seek pain treatment.
Thus, at the end of life, doctors often resort to terminal sedation, which involves either putting the patient to sleep sporadically or permanently until the time of his death.
We can no longer pretend that we don't see this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the option of resorting to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not relieved all say the same sentence, "I want to die".
But that doesn't necessarily mean, "I want you to put me to sleep", but, "I want my pain to be relieved".
