Bitcoin is a bank-free payment and sale
The opposite of the current monetary exchange on the basis of central banks, identified transactions and processing fees between the parties.
In addition, as so often in these technologies, a political vision is tangible: the belief that the current monetary system, designed by banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros, etc.) and a secure exchange protocol like BitTorrent that allows direct file exchange.
With 15,000 computers on the network, about 200,000 transactions have already been recorded.
A few thousand websites accept Bitcoin as a donation or payment method.
After peaking at $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, the price of Bitcoin dropped to $2 five months later before recovering to around $10 today (the prices are listed on bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing particularly impressive compared to world trade in real currencies or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
She describes Bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency", "competing with the dollar or euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies such as "credits", which are used to advance in a video game that you can win or buy through gaming (and sometimes exchange back).
The social network Facebook has also developed a system of this kind.
However, each trade is controlled and processed by a central authority.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously account holders, auditors, money issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users actually takes place between two email addresses in the form of an email.
The difference is that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A series of data related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double encryption system.
This allows the network to verify the authenticity of the transaction.
The contents of the file also make it possible to ensure that the traded bitcoins are in the public accounts ledger distributed throughout the network.
The crucial step is to include this new transaction in this book.
This is done through a mathematical task that is started on the computers, where the winner, who is a kind of provisional central banker, has the privilege of adding this additional line.
It is a fragmentation of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and clearer electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole thing is "hacked".
