We have received many complaints from our migrants.
"You will be promised the one at home, and on arrival you will be cheated, your passports taken away and you will not get the promised salary", confirms Tolib Schwaripow, head of the Tajik Migration Agency's chief labour migration office.
Don't be mean, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who want to earn money in Russia admit that they not only do not master the language of the destination country, but also can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as the problem: few Turkmen, Uzbeks and Tajik people can afford even a reasonable basic education.
Because their families do not even have money to feed their children, let alone buy them decent clothes, shoes, and school supplies.
As teenagers, these children immediately seize the first opportunity to earn money.
"It's hard without language skills", they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior".
Civil rights activists stress the following important aspect of the law.
Only legal immigrants have to take the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, the majority of guest workers continue to stay in Russia illegally.
"Welcome" or "No entry for unauthorized persons"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is the bureaucratic obstacles and, of course, the linguistic difficulties.
