Šimon Ornest: We want to gather positive energy at our concerts
What do you think about the world ending in less than a month?
This is one of those disaster reports that people like to jump to.
With our band The Tap Tap, we're more of a joke about it, saying that we're the only band in the world that can collect enough positive energy to stop or prevent the end of the world.
In December, you will also be hosting a unique project with three anti-concert concerts.
Can you introduce the project to our readers?
It's a national benefit event we've been planning for two years.
To do this, we want to use the marketing potential of the Mayan calendar, which is predicted to end at 11:10 a.m. on December 21.
On the day before, that is to say on 20 December, three concerts will be held simultaneously in Prague, Brno and Ostrava from 21:00.
The end of the concerts is supposed to be around the time when the Mayan calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, which is in a time zone 12 hours ahead of us.
Who came up with this idea?
I thought it was me, but then we came up with the idea with our graphic designer, Honza Augusta.
We want to not only gather enough positive energy to prevent the end of the world, but we also want to think with the public about what kind of world we will once give to our children.
To mark the end of the Mayan calendar, we also developed a unique collection of end-of-the-world shoes, T-shirts, bags and key hangers that people can buy on www.e-tap.cz to help us.
The band The Tap Tap has also recorded, along with other performers, the so-called "End of the World" anthem, entitled "End of the World Is Falling Out".
The anthem is already very popular on YouTube. Will it be played at the benefit concerts?
Of course, and it's all in the end, provided everything works out and the world doesn't end...
The anthem is to be sung simultaneously by all performers at all three concerts.
In addition, the anthems will be broadcast live together on Czech television.
The lyrics of the hymn are by Tomáš Hanák, who also plays the main character of Jesus in the video, Xindl X also sings with...
How did you get to work with them?
We also cooperate with other figures of the Czech cultural scene, which is linked to the fact that we have many charity events and concerts...
We're trying to get these people involved in our projects.
It has been shown that most people are interested in working with us and enjoy it.
What purpose does the proceeds from the concerts against the end of the world serve?
The project is aimed at the creation of the Studeo Barrier-Free Education Centre, where we have been working for six years together with the Tap Association at the Jedlička Institute.
Students of Jedlička Institute are regularly supervised by lecturers who assist them in various leisure activities.
Since the students themselves do not have the means to visit the lecturers, we want to help them in this way.
The project is to build a building for the Jedlička Institute, which we will then move into.
Every concert features several groups and performers.
What criteria did you use to choose these?
We wanted to put together a program that would appeal to all generations, including children.
In Prague, for example, there are Chinaski, Support Lesbians, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý.
You can find out more on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are similar "major events" planned for the future?
In May we will perform for the first time at Prague Spring, and we will also prepare an interesting programme for this concert with interesting guests.
We would like to perform at the Czech House in New York next year, and I personally, if we are in the United States, would like to associate this with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not very small, you have already performed in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap, however, is a group of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these journeys logistically and organisationally?
It's not as bad as it looks at first glance.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, which means wheelchairs must be carried in the luggage compartment, and we must of course bring a lot of instrument trunks and other luggage...
Nevertheless, until now it has always worked without problems, ČSA and British Airways were always very well prepared for us, which I have sometimes wondered at.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Your travels abroad will give you a comparison of what accessibility looks like in each country, how people with disabilities are treated there, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities where everything works better than ours, we have just witnessed in Russia that everything in the East is still in its infancy.
Moscow is not a handicapped city compared to Prague, where it is still unusual for a person to be in a wheelchair alone in the city centre.
It is not even natural to leave a wheelchair user in an elevator, for example.
Fortunately, there are also groups that try to raise awareness of the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what way do we have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There's a lot of stuff we're stuck with...
However, it should be noted that improving the situation always depends on the efforts of those concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is quite common for people with severe disabilities to move freely in public spaces, to go to museums, to use toilets, etc.
But it is not very common for a larger group of disabled people to take an active part in social events there, and we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect for the public and accessibility are one thing, but only when prominent athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come from our ranks will things really start to change.
So far, these are only individual cases of particularly strong-willed personalities.
The Tap is very popular right now, but if we go back a few years, what motivated you to start a band in 1998?
I started as a tutor at the Jedlička Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in doing something intensive.
And as a musician myself, I play saxophone, among other things, I started a music company with a colleague.
And over time, as our moderator, Láďa Angelovič, says, it got a little out of control.
But the band didn't really get to the attention of the public until the last few years, or am I wrong?
It is true that working with well-known singers has helped us; in addition, we have also started to actively promote ourselves.
We've come to realize that when you do something that you can't see from the outside, your own performance doesn't exist in some sense.
Thanks to EU funding, we can also afford good readers, high-quality equipment, etc.
Was it your goal to get this far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I felt the potential to approach things differently.
In show business today, people often copy each other.
This is logical in its own way, since everything new is considered with caution and only accepted after a long time.
There are few really unique things, and I dare say that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression the viewer usually has is, of course, pity; it's only natural...
But this pity is absolutely superfluous because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings that we should regret.
They are people who can live and develop a full life if they have the means to do so.
I always say that when people with disabilities succeed, it's not just a progress for themselves, but for the whole society.
Was it helpful for this success that you were a strict boss, as you hear from many people?
If you want to do something well, you must not compromise on many things and you must also require some discipline.
But I think this is quite normal.
Some come to us with romantic performances, and when they find that they have rehearsals twice a week, they have to go through preparatory stages and spend a lot of time on concert tours, the excitement in many quickly fades.
But that's how it works everywhere, in every band that's serious about working and trying to get something done.
The Tap Tap currently has 20 members.
How many of these were there from the beginning, i.e. since 1998?
There's only one, Lada Angelovic.
We're an open group, people come and go, and you can't stop that.
Anyone who has the will and the desire to join is always welcome.
