Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was admitted to the European Space Agency's 20th membership at a meeting of the Council of Ministers of the ESA member countries, making it the second member country from the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became ESA member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began working closely with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
Poland's journey into space began much earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish cosmologists were interested in space travel, but they did not always understand it.
I remember, for example, the lecture given by A. Šternfeld at the Warsaw Observatory on 6 December 1933, in which the author presented ideas from his pioneering work "Entry to Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the audience cold, and after years Šternfeld still remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch, founded by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch, for "Entrance into Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899-1966) later became an important proponent of astronomy and space travel.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky's world-renowned contribution to space travel was recognized, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the lunar surface was named after him.
In 1925, a railway drainage system was built in Poland, for which a rocket propulsion system was planned.
The author of the draft and the details of this project remain unknown.
It's not even clear whether the rocket should be used to launch or to brake the drill.
The information on this comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-propelled shells.
The research was carried out by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
The documents submitted show that the research had progressed to the stage of practical testing.
The research was interrupted by the German invasion.
In 1937 the design of a photoelectric fighter missile by Ing. Rohoziński appeared in the trade press, and the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects concerned the military use of rocket propulsion.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of missile technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Committee Doradczo-Naukowy).
The Committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of work its work was terminated by the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space were published in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of this society is found in the November 1954 issue of Problemy magazine, which devoted four extensive articles to space travel.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to set up a space company.
At that time, the first satellite projects were already underway, and it was expected that space exploration would have a future.
Already from its inception in 1956, the Polish Space Agency PTA was seeking membership in the International Space Federation, founded in 1951, and in fact the PTA became a full member in autumn 1956.
The following year, the first PTA president, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959), became Vice-President of the International Federation for Space.
He held this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been instrumental in the development of the highly successful Meteorological Missile (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish missile for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, with the first launch on 10 October 1958.
The rocket, with a maximum flight altitude of 1,800 m, was about 80 cm long and weighed less than 5 kg.
Later an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959 flight tests began in the Błędów desert with the two-stage RM-2 rocket.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and weighed about 11.5 kilograms.
A further stage of development should already be capable of providing real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach a flight altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used for observing high winds.
However, further development was halted in 1962.
The successor to the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965.
The missile was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and a launch weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types of this missile were developed (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a carrying capacity of 0.4 litres, the Meteor-1B 0.34 litres and the Meteor-1C 0.62 litres.
The maximum altitude for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aviation Institute, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a launch weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
After that, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning that Poland joined the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, followed two years later by the creation of a national COSPAR committee.
Poland also participated in the Intercosmos programme in space exploration using Soviet satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladimír Remek.
