Szabo: "Germans need to play a bigger role"
Germany voted in favour of the accession of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on U.S.-European relations, Berlin balances this on a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany initially signaled that it would vote against the request for Palestinian observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin was in the dark.
Why? Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
But now Germany must be careful because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don't think it supports the American position.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - but without being too critical of Israel.
During the March 2011 uprising in Libya, Germany also abstained from voting when it was asked to establish a no-fly zone.
This was finally enforced by NATO.
Does Germany find it difficult to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yes, that's right.
This is because it is now converting its foreign policy away from a policy that is, as it were, managed by the United States into a German foreign policy.
The European Union is not a single country, but it is a country that is not a single country.
The Germans are now between the fronts.
They're expected to play a more independent role, but they're not used to it.
I think they are still working on their role, but they are on the way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy like France or Britain.
What is the meaning of a "normal" foreign policy from the German point of view?
It is willing to take positions that are independent of those of the United States or European partners in the interests of national interests.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, that is, by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to some extent different from those of the other great powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the attitude in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
Firstly, Germany has large sales markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
So we must be careful not to put the public, but also the elites in the Arab countries, in the head.
That certainly does matter.
But I wouldn't want to put too much weight on that either, because that's not a one-sided relationship.
But it certainly plays an important role in German thinking.
Did Germany damage its relations with the United States by abstaining from voting on important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that in Europe and even in the United States there is a great understanding of the German position.
I therefore do not believe that this was a dramatic break as in the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will even gain some respect.
Because it signals that as an international player, he needs to be taken seriously and his interests taken into account.
There are different opinions in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
The United States, on the other hand, has clearly voted for a veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the United States and many European nations?
Because of American domestic policy, these differences have always existed.
I think the Obama administration has a pretty good understanding of the European position.
But given the political situation here, the government cannot, of course, publicly represent this position.
I think the actual differences of opinion are not as great as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not so enthusiastic about Netanyahu's policies.
Does Germany find it difficult to agree on its close relations with Israel and the United States on the one hand and the position of the most important partners in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes it so hard for the Germans.
It would be a little easier for the Germans, of course, if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, which is not the case at the moment.
So they can't be part of a broader line and instead have to push things from their own position.
They're doing that with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will play a leading role in pushing Europe towards a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, of course, because of its relationship with Israel.
It's always been a sensitive subject.
But I think the Germans are aware that they need to play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself as an important international player in the role - does Germany want to take a leading role at all?
Or is Germany still a difficult leader?
Germany is not yet used to this, which is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for it to play a larger role.
The European Parliament has also been able to make a number of proposals to the Council.
It's not easy for the Germans.
That's the old problem, actually: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It must be responsive to the widest possible range of neighbors and opinions, and that's not easy.
Now the influence of the United States in European politics is continually declining, but the EU is not filling this vacuum at the moment, who else is left?
The Germans will simply have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don't like it, they feel uncomfortable and it makes them much less popular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America collaborate on the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he has specialized in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
