Before he came to terms with the US president, Pena Nieto was governor of his home state of Mexico.
In this densely populated, vast part of the country that surrounds the capital, opinions are divided about the new head of state.
A straight man
For example, in the remote small town of Valle del Bravo, people like to remember him.
Residents of the resort attribute to it the development of tourism and the construction of infrastructure.
To reach the city, you can take one of the highways built by Pena Nieto, which is a major improvement over the fragile, bumpy roads that once existed here.
Posters bearing his name hang outside a modern sports centre and an impressive interactive climate change museum.
"We expect real and lasting changes from him", said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, who is a member of Congress for the PRI party, Pena Nietos.
In particular, as regards security and the economy, we hope for the interesting and real change that our country needs so urgently.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was replaced in 2000 by Vicente Fox.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the presidential palace of Los Pinos, the party has high expectations of Enrique Pena Nieto.
He rejects the opposition's accusations that the new president lacks substance.
He's a very direct man, very committed and has big plans for the country.
He is an excellent statesman, but above all he is also someone who can listen.
But on the other side of the state, not many people share this view of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast to the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
The site is hidden beneath highway traffic and is in many ways a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the community are of a decisive urban nature.
Earlier this year, the military was activated to fight the drug gangs operating in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is a particularly acute problem.
In the last two years alone, dozens of murdered women have been left behind on a patch of land near a large landfill.
During the tenure of Governor Pena Nieto, over 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico - a statistic that surpasses even the city of Ciudad Juarez, which is notorious for its violence and the murder of innocent women.
Pena Nietos' critics believe that he has not at least adequately addressed the issue of women's murder during his term in office.
But at worst, his government has closed its eyes to the problem.
In a concrete building typical of the downtown area, Irinea Buendia struggles with tears as she shows me pictures of her late daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official story, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
But her family believes she was murdered by her life partner.
"When I arrived at her home, it seemed as if her body had been washed", recalls Senora Buendia.
There were signs that she had been beaten, and the corpse rig had already been used.
As her mother tells her story, a picture of Mariana looks down at us from the wall, and it's placed next to a cross that carries a single word: justice.
But this is exactly what the family says she's been denied so far.
The authorities treated me like I was a talkie, a troublemaker, a nerd.
They want you to accept their verdict and keep your mouth shut.
"But that's not possible with so many mistakes and failures", she says.
If President Pena Nieto receives the Presidency on Saturday, he will also assume a great responsibility.
Tens of thousands of Mexican families have been plagued by violent crime in the past six years, and the new president has vowed to take special care of this problem during his term.
"I hope as president he is as he was as governor", says PRI congressman Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
But that's what the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza fear most.
Prosecutors say Bradley Manning did not complain of abuse.
Prosecutors dispute Bradley Manning's allegations that he was mistreated in prison.
The hearing is about Manning's time in military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defence seeks to dismiss the charges on the grounds of harsh conditions of detention
The US Army's jailer is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents
Prosecutors tried Friday to find that Army Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest disclosure of classified information in U.S. history, missed several occasions to complain about the alleged abuse he suffered in military custody.
During a cross-examination of Manning during a pre-trial hearing in Fort Meade, Maryland, Maj. Ashden Fein stated that records of weekly visits made by prison officials during Manning's nine-month imprisonment in Quantico, Virginia, showed no complaints about his treatment.
One day before the cross-examination, which was held following a request from the defence to dismiss the charges - Manning had already been sufficiently punished by the harsh prison sentence - Manning had testified that he had considered suicide in prison.
The US Army intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of classified documents during his time in Iraq.
The material was then published by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed Manning as the source of the information.
At Friday's hearing, Mr. Fein reviewed the forms officials filled out after meeting Mr. Manning during his time in custody at the Quantico Military Prison, where he was held under strict conditions from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When asked about the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he had judged the treatment by his guards to be "excellent" and the treatment by the facility as a whole to be "very professional".
The forms, Fine said, contained no complaints of abuse, although the officials had directly questioned Manning about his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns orally and that officials had discussed them with him and indicated that they were dealing with them, but that they had not been recorded.
"They wrote down (after discussing the concerns) 'No problems,' and that didn't necessarily mean I said anything at all", Manning said.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he hadn't complained about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to investigate the suicidal thoughts he mentioned on a form a few months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during this meeting was to reduce his observation status to 'injury prevention'.
The military said it had assigned him this restrictive status - one level below the suicide risk - to protect himself and others.
"I wanted to convince employees that I was doing well and to get rid of injury prevention observation status . . . so that I could achieve a higher quality of life", Manning said.
Manning announced his arrest and deportation to Kuwait on Thursday, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the Quantico Naval Base prison in Virginia in July 2010.
He said he was thinking about suicide in Kuwait and had passed out in the heat.
Not knowing what was happening to him or the outside world was stressful.
"My world shrank to Camp Arafjon, to this cage", Manning said Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in this cage.
When he was transferred to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell - at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours - and without company.
All he was allowed to do was use a mattress, a blanket, flip flops, clothes and glasses.
Manning said he tried to stay in motion because during the day it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down.
He always had to sleep with light penetrating his cell from the outside.
When he turned around at night and the guards could no longer see his face, they woke him up to turn back.
In January 2011, Manning's lawyer formally objected to Manning's treatment.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to the military prison at Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
On Friday, Judge Manning also questioned Manning about an accusation he made in his statement on Thursday - that he slept naked one night in his cell in Quantico and had to stand naked before guards and other prisoners at a morning count.
Manning had testified that he had never had the opportunity to cover himself with his blanket during this count.
During the interview on Friday, Manning said he had concluded from a warrant issued by his guard that he should drop the ceiling he could have covered himself with, but he admitted that no one had asked him to.
On Thursday, Manning testified that he was forced to sleep naked the night before, and that he had tried to show an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning told the officer that he could have used the fuse of his underwear or his flip flops to hurt himself, but he didn't.
That night, Manning said, his underwear, flip flops and glasses were removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account his experience in prison and drastically reduce his sentence should he be convicted in his trial before the military court, which is scheduled for early next year.
The defense has indicated that Manning will plead guilty to lesser charges while challenging other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is scheduled to resume this weekend and the prosecutor's office is expected to justify the conditions of detention.
The Pentagon maintains that Manning was detained under the provisions applicable to all detainees held under the highest security measures in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include favouring the enemy, illegally publishing intelligence on the Internet, transmitting national defense information, and stealing public property or documents.
If he is found guilty on all charges, he faces a life sentence.
My Mexican-American identity crisis.
Many people were forced to leave Mexico because of the lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to blame immigrants - they remind them of difficult times, he says
Navarrette believes that Mexican Americans are trapped between two worlds
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had just crossed the hall and arrived at the passport checkpoint when disorientation spread.
The signs pointed to two queues: one for "Mexicanos" ("Mexicanos") and another for "Extranjeros" ("Foreigners").
I was there for a few seconds, unsure of which direction to turn.
I grew up in central California and have been called a Mexican all my life.
An ethnic acronym -- just like my friends in Boston call themselves "Iren" or my friends in New York call themselves "Italians".
Later, I decided to go with "Mexican American".
But this was Mexico.
And in my grandfather's home, there was no need for shorts or bandages.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish, at least well enough to speak it at both ends of an interview.
But I don't have the vocabulary of a native speaker, and I'm not going to get rid of my American accent either.
So I took my American passport and lined up for aliens.
I was thinking about that moment this week when the future Mexican president, Enrique Pena Nieto, visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
The agenda included all the topics that are expected when the heads of these two countries meet: immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto was also very interested in talking about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one reason why Mexicans are just as likely to stay in Mexico today as to emigrate to the United States.
He wants to join forces with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade bloc modelled on the European Union.
And Pena Nieto vowed to continue Mexico's war on the drug cartels, even if he didn't give any details.
Mexico's relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never waste a single thought of the United States invading Mexico in 1848 and forcing the country's leadership under pretended fire to cede more than half of its territory to them.
But for Mexicans who think in centuries and not minutes, memories of this event are not to be overlooked.
So once a U.S. government official makes the slightest criticism of Mexico, you hear complaints in the Mexican press and among the country's elites about how the Americans are suppressing the sovereignty of their neighboring country.
And the children of Montezuma are on the path of war.
And yet, the biggest challenge for Mexico is actually in the relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
You want to talk about resentment?
There's more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers, people for whom the country offers opportunities, and others for whom it does not.
The only reason so many people of Mexican descent live in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver, or San Antonio is that at some point in our family tree, a person -- maybe a parent or grandparent -- didn't get a chance to live in Mexico and migrated north.
And in most cases, this person matched a profile -- dark-skinned, uneducated, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of these people, and our loyalty is to them.
Not Mexico.
And while we may now be living the American Dream, attending good schools and getting good jobs, we must never lose sight of the fact that it is the American Dream we are living - not the Mexican Dream.
Our identity may be blurred at times, but when it comes to our loyalty, it is not.
This clearly applies to the United States.
We also know that many members of the Mexican leadership do not like us.
This is based on reciprocity.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and look down on us because we're not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In your opinion, our existence is a symbol of failure.
If our families hadn't failed in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
And then we wouldn't be trapped behind the silk curtain now - with a pleasant life in the United States, but still somehow lost.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and immigrated to the United States legally as a child, reminds me that there is tension between Mexicans and Mexican Americans because Mexicans have a clearer idea of who they are - and Mexican Americans take it badly.
While she is a US citizen, she sees herself as part of two countries.
But many Mexican Americans I know feel that they belong neither to one country nor to another.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but we also love Bruce Springsteen.
You enjoy the best of both worlds, but you're not rooted in either.
In Mexico, we're seen as Americans.
And in the United States, we're seen as Mexicans.
As I should have learned during my trip, there is something that makes this relationship even more complicated: some Mexican leaders and parts of the education community want to reestablish their ties to the diaspora.
They want to use Mexican Americans as temporary "ambassadors" for Mexico to represent their interests in the United States.
We should tell our American colleagues how great a visit to this country is and pressure the political leadership to intensify their ties to Mexico.
Well, I guess.
It's not gonna happen.
Too many hurt feelings.
And given the unfair distribution of income, the rampant corruption and drug abuse, many of us are not so sure if this is a great country.
I'm afraid you'll have to go through this alone, Amigos.
That's fair.
If at least some Mexicans are not yet willing to forgive the United States for dealing with Mexico a century and a half ago, they must also accept that some Mexican Americans resent the way their family members were treated not so long ago.
I'm not going to.
Maybe we're more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could prove to be an unexpected cornerstone of peace
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
The latest bloody events seem to stifle such hope in the seed.
Amid the usual accusations, countless buildings have been thrown into the ground, more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis killed - and for the first time, rockets from Gaza have hit near the Israeli capital Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
Yet, although Israelis and Palestinians seem to be trapped in their historic conflict, the Middle East is changing around them.
The Arab Spring has created a new, uncertain situation, and whether they like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis have become part of this mess.
Maybe this will only lead to more bloodshed.
But there is reason to believe that the deadly situation may finally come to an end.
A War Neither Lost nor Won
At first glance, optimism seems far from appropriate in view of the current situation.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on November 21 continues, this week's fighting has strengthened the hardliners on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has controlled Gaza since 2007, claim to have pushed back Israelis even though their group itself suffered heavy losses.
Despite the killing of several Hamas leaders and the 1.7 million inhabitants of Gaza being trapped in one of the most desolate and densely populated corners of the planet, Israel has so far failed to destroy Hamas.
Indeed, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, which is controlled by the rival moderate Palestinian group Fatah.
And the Hamas leaders might conclude that they have time on their side.
Just as Islamists have gained influence in the Arab world, Hamas has been able to attract powerful and wealthy friends to its side.
Turkey, a recovering regional power once considered Israel's closest Muslim ally, has joined Hamas - just like Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Cheerful Hamas supporters believe that an Islamist crescent is forming around Israel - from Lebanon in the north, where militant Hezbollah has power, to Syria, where rebels of an increasingly Islamist character could face the overthrow of Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
And in particular, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Muhammad Mursi in Egypt - by far the most populous and important Arab country - on Israel's southern flank has changed the balance of the region in a lasting way.
Hosni Mubarak, the secularist despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had little time left for Hamas.
In contrast, the Brotherhood is more aligned with Hamas and its leaders are more dependent on popular views.
In future diplomatic negotiations Hamas could prove to be an actor that Israel and the United States themselves cannot push out.
The Israeli hardliners, on the other hand, draw the opposite conclusion.
From a military point of view, Hamas is no longer a threat.
The Israeli missile defense system, the Iron Dome, has proven itself and many of the Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
At least for a while, Israel will be able to sleep more peacefully.
The United States has maintained its position in a diplomatic sense, and many European countries have blamed Hamas for the latest escalation of violence.
Israel has done well in recent years, especially under Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from the Gaza Strip have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, the country has remained relatively free from suicide bombers - not least thanks to the blockade facilities that have penetrated the West Bank and thus the mainland of any Palestinian state, which protect Jewish settlements that have been declared illegal under international law but are continuing to expand.
Netanyahu is doing well, and his Likud party has allied itself with an even more militant group ahead of the January 22 elections, led by Avigdor Lieberman.
Why should these cunning Palestinians be harassed and left with their own state?
If they were in control of the West Bank, wouldn't they be firing missiles like their fellow soldiers in Gaza?
No, it's better to hold them behind the wall and punish them if they dare to lift their heads.
Maybe the hardliners will be able to make a move, but the Arab Spring could make a dent in their numbers.
Even if the Islamists who are now in power in Egypt and other countries have little left for Israel, they will focus first on the difficulties in their own country.
Israel's defense is bigger than its four Arab neighbors combined.
A war with the local superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments to rebuild their economies.
That the pragmatic President Morsi has teamed up with Barack Obama to achieve a ceasefire could be a promising sign - and perhaps symbolize the beginning of a new era.
Israelis should think longer term too.
While the rest of the Arab world is taking bold steps toward democratization, Palestinians continue to be deprived of their right to self-determination - a powder keg that will undoubtedly explode one day in the Israeli-occupied territories, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
The oppression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state, and with the growth of the Arab population, this situation will only worsen.
Bloody missions to repel Hamas in the Gaza Strip will increasingly demand diplomatic tribute over the years.
Both sides need an outside push.
The correct answer is that of the more reasonable representatives of both sides, of most of the rest of the world and of this newspaper: two states where Israel is relinquishing territory for security reasons.
The hope - small for the near future - is that the ceasefire will give outsiders more influence in enforcing this solution.
Egypt must now, together with Turkey and Qatar, stop arms supplies to the Gaza Strip and is better positioned than ever to convince Hamas of the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, complemented by land exchange and a shared Jerusalem.
Foreign Arab nations should also push Hamas and Fatah to an agreement.
This would be more to do for the creation of a Palestinian state than with the forthcoming request for UN observer status.
Obama must also play his part in moving Israel to negotiations.
During his first term, he missed the idea of his own peace plan.
Far away in the White House, it seems he's equally averse to participation.
But that's a regrettable, shortsighted prospect.
The United States has a substantial interest in a stable Middle East.
And that includes a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Australian laws on uniform cigarette packaging come into force
Health warnings and sick parts on neutral green packaging, identical for all tobacco brands
The first uniform laws for cigarette and tobacco packaging in the world came into force in Australia, replacing brand logos and colours with neutral olive-green covers, which are also printed with drastic images showing sick body parts and infants and children who are sick from cigarette smoke.
As from next Saturday, apart from the various health warnings and images, the only difference between the packages in the brand names, which are printed in identical small letters, is that they are not identical.
Australia has introduced the strictest tobacco packaging regulations in the world.
The Australian federal government wants to stop young people from smoking by eliminating the glamorous image of tobacco use.
The government is based on studies that have shown that people who haven't started smoking by age 26 are 99% likely to quit after that.
"You can already see that young children understand the message of trying to promote tobacco companies with their brand image", says Tanya Plibersek, the Federal Minister of Health.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and the changes will have only a slight impact on the profits of multinational corporations, other countries are already considering similar steps.
The tobacco club fought hard against the laws.
It was said that the laws would favour the black market trade, which would lead to cheaper and more accessible cigarettes.
"The laws will have serious, unintended consequences", says Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Chinese and Indonesian counterfeiters will be offering far greater quantities of these products on the streets of Australia.
Others, on the other hand, say that the laws have upset their business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, notes that the demand for cigarette tubes and silicone lids to cover the intolerable packaging has increased dramatically since British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco failed to challenge the laws in the Australian Supreme Court two months ago.
Zico has sold up to 6,000 units to wholesale stores and is waiting for new stocks.
It's a good deal for us.
Experts say that the social media's popularity is tied to the specific population targeted by the plan.
A series of Australian laws have banned tobacco companies from TV advertising, prohibiting them from acting as sports sponsors, and forcing most retailers to stop selling cigarettes in stores.
The Australian government has banned internet advertising by local businesses and sites, but has no influence on international sites.
"If you're marketing tobacco and you only have a small area left to promote your products, you're not going to get around the Internet", says Becky Freeman, a health researcher at the University of Sydney.
On social media such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook, Freeman has seen an increase in brand experiences written by "totally normal people".
You have to ask yourself, is this just a private person who likes Marlboro cigarettes so much that she even makes a video for them, or is there a marketing agency involved?
British American Tobacco Australia says that the industry is focused on dealing with the new laws rather than marketing.
It has even gone so far as to pay Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules - those countries complain to the World Trade Organization about unfair trade restrictions, even though none of them have a greater trade relationship with Australia.
A WTO decision is expected in mid-2013.
According to Plibersek, the government has been in talks with other countries considering similar packaging laws.
In 2001, Canada was the first country to require photographic warnings.
These have now been extended to more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
Tighter laws are being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many Australian smokers are defiant.
The pictures don't affect me.
I just ignore them.
"You just take a cigarette butcher and put the box away", says Victor El Hage, buying a cigarette box with a picture of a mouth tumor.
Honestly, there's only one reason I'd stop, and that's my little girl.
James Yu, who runs the King of the Pack tobacco shop in downtown Sydney, says that the uniform packaging has made it harder to fill his shelves.
"I used to need an hour to sort out a shipment, now I need four", Yu says.
"The government should have just banned cigarettes completely - then we would have said okay, that's it, we're closing", he adds, apparently regretting.
In a world that's always electrified, it's nice to be bored sometimes.
This Thanksgiving, I unexpectedly spent five hours at the airport when our plane crashed due to mechanical problems and we had to wait for another plane.
So I had enough time to think about a few things.
I don't want to lie to you.
Waiting at the airport for a flight for half a day is quite annoying - even when books, magazines, and iPhones (and, of course, tax-free shopping) are available.
But more and more academics and child development experts are calling boredom a positive thing.
When it comes to them, it's okay for us - and our kids - to get bored occasionally.
It forces the brain to lose itself in interesting thought processes, which may stimulate creativity.
And because most of us today are staring at one or another screen almost all the time, we no longer benefit from the benefits of boredom.
So should we welcome boredom with open arms?
- I know.
And no, I did not.
I'll come back to that.
Like many people, I have always assumed that boredom is a relatively recent phenomenon that has evolved with increasing leisure time.
But Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of "Boredom: A Lively History" (Yale University Press, 2011), does not see it that way.
"In fact, boredom has a very long history", he says.
The walls of Pompeii's houses are decorated with a Latin graffiti of boredom dating back to the first century.
And then there's the question of how we define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After reading research literature for a long time and presenting the idea to a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues concluded that boredom can be defined as the experience of "wishing to do a satisfying activity but not being able to do it".
Boredom differs from apathy in that the person is not busy but wants to be.
Apathy, on the other hand, is not a drive to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, is "a disturbance of the attentional process, coupled with a bad mood and a feeling that time is passing by slowly".
Boredom can sound almost like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes that while these two conditions may be related, bored people see the problem in their environment or the world, while depressed people see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we're bored, even when we're just having trouble concentrating.
In their study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", published in September in the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues point to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape of a person reading a magazine article.
Some groups heard a loud TV program from the neighboring room that had nothing to do with the content; others listened to it at low volume, so it was hardly noticeable, while the third group did not hear those sounds at all.
The people who rarely listened to the television reported feeling more bored than the other two groups - they had trouble concentrating, could not find a reason for it, and attributed their difficulties to boredom.
When trying to focus on a difficult or stressful task, distracted attention can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study's authors.
On the other hand, when you do a monotonous activity - "like looking for faulty products on a factory tape - music can distract and help you not feel bored".
In fact, he says, we now know that whining and screaming, often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can even combat it by keeping people more physically alert.
"Studies have shown that children who are allowed to walk around learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still", says Professor Fenske.
We all get bored at some point - my late flight, a loudspeaker, a particularly tiring movie.
But some people get bored more easily than others.
To measure these differences, researchers developed a "boredom sensitivity scale" in the 1980s.
On the scale, you can find statements like, "A lot of things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous", and, "I have so many interests that I don't have enough time for everything".
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys are more likely to get bored than girls, says Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida - particularly when it comes to the need for more and more variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teenagers are a pretty tense bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day with a pager.
He found that 32 percent of adolescents were bored at school and doing their homework, while 23 percent reported being bored when they weren't at school.
Yet, only 3 percent of parents reported feeling bored.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, he doesn't know if the boredom percentages have gone up or down.
He is sure, however, that "youth is perceived as particularly boring", mainly because children and teenagers have little influence on their daily lives.
So back to my original question: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases, it causes people to take extreme physical risks and resort to gambling or drugs to mitigate them, studies have shown.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers study the relationship between boredom and creativity, according to Professor Vodanovich, who has been researching the subject for more than two decades.
"When you get bored, your brain wants to tell you to do something different", says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
But the brain doesn't always know what the best thing to do is right now.
If you're bored and you use that energy to play guitar and cook, you'll be happy.
But while television can provide short-term happiness, it can fade in the long run.
So if you give your bored child an iPad, you can help him get rid of boredom, but he hasn't learned to talk or control himself, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds: "Self-control is a transition from one situation to another".
Not only does the child learn to communicate, but he also gains more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
We should not be too critical of them either.
Instead, our goal should be to feel comfortable away from the constant distraction of activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees with that.
"It sounds like we're more likely to get bored, but boredom is the tormenting, unrelenting desire to do something meaningful", he says.
He believes that people are really just looking for a way to turn off and relax.
"In an environment where we are constantly over-stimulated, it is difficult to be busy once the noise is silenced".
In Colorado, there's no clear guideline for the new marijuana law.
Nineteen-year-old community college student and football player Anthony Orozco is on trial in southeastern Colorado for a crime that will soon be legal in that state: the possession of a few small pieces of marijuana and a pipe he used to smoke.
Orozco said he and some friends were driving to Lamar, near the Kansas border, on a September day when they were stopped.
After the police officer found marijuana in the car, Orozco was charged with possession of drugs and drug paraphernalia - criminal offences punishable by a fine of $100 each - and was given a court date.
"We are treated like criminals", Orozco said.
But is he one?
In the uncertain weeks following the state's decision to legalize small amounts of marijuana for personal use, the answer to hundreds of smaller drug offenses depends less on the law than on the location.
Hundreds of marijuana-related offenses are already being dropped here and in Washington State, which has approved similar measures.
The police authorities no longer pursue adults over 21 for possession to a lesser extent, which will be allowed by law once the new laws come into force in the coming weeks.
But prosecutors in the more conservative counties of Colorado have announced they're continuing to prosecute existing marijuana offenses and are still citing people in court.
At the same time, several cities, from the Denver suburbs to the Western Mountains, have voted to prevent new, state-licensed marijuana businesses from opening in their communities.
"This situation is moving so fast that I don't know what's next", says Daniel J. Oates, police chief in Aurora, east of Denver.
And regulators in Washington state are scratching their heads.
They are awaiting guidance on the setting up of a licensing system for the production, manufacture, distribution and sale of the drug - and have a deadline of 1 December 2013.
In Washington, Colorado is considered to be in any case ahead of most states in regulating marijuana, where the drug was first legalized for medical purposes and then for personal use.
"Colorado has a more regulated market, so the state is well suited to navigation", says Brian E. Smith, spokesman for the D.C. State Department of Alcohol Control.
