But within two weeks of entering Worsester College in the late 1980's - where I had planned to study history - I had packed my suitcases again, causing the first scandal of my life.
My father broke down in tears.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard said I left because I had a problem with having sex with fellow roommates in the next room.
Author A. N. Wilson said slanderously that I had left the university because I was forced to drink from damaged cups.
But the truth was less amusing.
I ran away.
Yeah, I ran, because I was bullied and threatened.
Not because of my unusual name, or because I came from a private school.
I had been harassed for one reason only - one reason that seemed even more narrow and cruel in this supposed cradle of enlightenment: My late father Woodrow Wyatt had been a key adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I was a supporter of the Conservative Party.
Why am I mentioning this right now?
Well, according to recent reports, a new generation of moderate-right students are suffering similar persecution.
The organized and growing hatred of Tory students at Oxford has now developed to such an extent that a group of them last week called for equal protection for gays, disabled people and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of the Junior Common Room (JCR) of Corpus Christi College say they are "often actively isolated, personally attacked and declared unwanted" because of their political views.
They are asking for a seat on their college's equality committee to ensure that their views can be freely expressed.
Their situation was made worse by a recent documentary on political students on BBC Two, "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right", which depicted Tories as eccentric and neo-Nazi.
It featured, among others, graduate Joe Cooke, former president of the conservative Oxford University student union, who was riding a Rolls-Royce and wearing a silver suit and a silver-colored walking stick.
At other universities, conservative students say they are considered "sinner goats for the introduction of higher tuition fees".
The 20-year-old Luke Black, vice-president of the Conservative Students' Association at the University of Nottingham, told a Sunday newspaper: "There is a growing leftist trend in universities.
People think we're like the Bullingdon Club without ever knowing each other".
Samuel Roberts, 21, a Corpus Christi history student who initiated the search for greater protection, believes that such a climate is "unpleasant". 19-year-old Stephanie Cherill, president-elect of the Conservative Students' Association of Oxford, says she has observed a growing rejection of moderate-right students among JCR members.
"This poses a danger to intellectual discourse and to the well-being of members", she says.
In my first few weeks at Oxford, I was part of such a minority.
I arrived in September 1986 at the age of 18 and was incredibly shy.
The hatred of the Conservative Party had reached its peak.
Last year, the university voted not to award an honorary degree to Margaret Thatcher, a former student, because of the cutbacks in higher education.
The atmosphere would have scared even Stalinists.
