They're fighting each other, aren't they?
I felt the way homosexuals must have felt before the more liberal legislation in the United States.
Would I ever manage to lead a normal life at Oxford University?
Could I meet with my peers after dark?
Should I turn to the Labour Party and suppress my natural inclinations?
The three years that lay ahead of me stretched out before my spiritual eye into a fiery furnace of rejection and isolation.
The only tutor who openly identified himself as a Tory was Norman Stone, a professor of contemporary history who had his seat at my college.
He was hated not only for being a conservative, but also for advising Thatcher on foreign policy and writing speeches for her.
He was rarely there.
He hated the place, found it provincial and small-town, and rejected it for its Marxist-determinist historical perspective.
In 1997, he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
"You won't be happy here", he told me.
I began to commute between Oxford and my parents' house, and I took refuge with more open-minded friends and family members in the city.
I told my father I hated Oxford and why I did it.
He seemed unbelieving.
During his time in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
"But it's the best place in the world", he said low.
They would never do such a thing, not in my dream town of tower towers.
Even my communist friends were always showing perfect manners.
His wet eyes were blurring.
Give it a chance.
I'm sure you're just being fucked.
It would break my heart if you left.
Tired of my frequent travels to London, my emotional resistance weakened.
One of my male friends, also a Tory, had succumbed to pressure and renounced his beliefs.
During a lecture the following week, where another history teacher seriously claimed that I was "an enemy of the people", I decided to do the same.
Although I was secretly crushed by shame, I admitted that my parents had brainwashed me, calling them "old idiots".
The relief was short-lived.
It was my father who hit the last nail in the coffin of my Oxford career.
At the time, he was writing two columns a week in the Murdoch press.
My door was locked.
I hid in my room, and after five minutes, my rabbits gave up.
