"Valentino prefers elegance to fame"
On the occasion of the exhibition "Valentino - Master of Couture", which opened this week in London, ABC is speaking to Naty Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza and other famous customers of the Italian fashion designer.
Somerset House, the former residence of Elizabeth I of England, is the only place in the British capital worthy of hosting an exhibition on Valentino Garavani.
This was acknowledged by the designer at the opening of "Valentino Masters of Couture", a grand retrospective that has assembled more than 130 high-end costumes created by his "maison" over the past 50 years.
"I love this palace", he says with his distinctive Italian accent.
This exhibition concludes a story whose only protagonist is "il signore" Garavani, but which could not have been written without his distinguished client.
Valentino has always been fascinated by the remote and sticky world of the nobility.
The first room of this exhibition, which will be on view until March 3, features a large number of private letters and photographs with the signature of the most distinguished aristocracy, from Princess Salimah Aga Khan to Princess Marie-Chantal of Greece and Margaret of England to Lord Snowdon.
Valentino presents these personal memories as trophies of his social rise from modest fashion designer in the northern Italian city of Voghera to international jet idol.
Being in love with the nobility doesn't have to be disadvantageous.
"At least they don't perform their tips on your gorgeous rug like some beautiful pop stars do", says Baroness Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza.
In the '60s and '70s, the two lived in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is a spectacular, generous and elegant host.
"We were all happy to be invited to his house in Gstaad", explains the ex-wife of "Heini" Thyssen, who is close friends with forgotten beauties such as Marella Agnelli or Eugenie Niarchos.
Valentino has always preferred the elegance of fame.
And yet he's a star.
Valeria Mazza, in a dress by Valentino
The Argentine model Valeria Mazza also remembers the fashion designer's charisma.
Many years ago, after a fashion show in Rome, we went to his house for dinner.
We were about 20 people, including Sharon Stone and John Kennedy Jr.
His influence was evident in every detail of his apartment, in the decorations, in the food, in the music.
"All the guests felt important and loved", recalls the "top model", who began her career at Haute Couture Week in Paris in 1995.
"It never goes out of fashion because its designs are works of art", she concludes.
Fashion of origin
Garavani's life is not a story of madness, but rather of mutual love.
He likes people with good education and the highest titles, and they love him.
One of the galleries at Somerset House has been transformed into a glorious, 60-meter-long runway that suggests a role replacement: the user takes the model's place and walks along the runway to admire a dreamlike "audience" wearing Valentino's masterpieces, such as the dress Jackie Kennedy chose for her wedding to Aristotle Onassis, the costumes Monica Vitti wore in "La Notte", or a coat of wool and leather made by Empress Farah Diba.
In this fashion puppet audience, names like Sibilla of Luxembourg, Gloria of Thurn and Taxis, Mette-Marit of Norway, Rosario of Bulgaria or Sofía of Habsburg shine.
Naty Abascal and the fashion designer, 2006
