The most difficult profession in the world: the human working animals of Kawah-ijen
For four euros, the Indonesian volcano's bearers risk their lives and health carrying 70 kilograms of sulfur across the steep, rocky paths.
There are people who work for hell, and others work literally in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of 400 miners who earn their living by extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, he must climb down to the bottom of his crater every day, where the sulfuric gas that flows from the earth in contact with the air solidifies.
After he has broken out large stones of sulfur, which can weigh up to 70 pounds [70 kg] in total, he carries them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders along the shallow stone paths.
While it is only 250 metres to the top of the volcano, which rises to an altitude of 2,386 metres, the exhausted tortoise carrier takes more than 40 minutes to climb up the pace, while maintaining balance and carefully setting its steps so as not to slip and fall.
They know that every step can cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who crashed years ago on the slopes of the Kawah Ijen.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 eurocents for every kilo of sulfur they mine.
They're going up, they're going down the path between tourists who photograph them like circus monkeys and they're walking with the tiringly heavy baskets three kilometers up to the scale that a mining company has set up a little further down at an altitude of 1,850 meters
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, which has been exploiting the volcano's resources since 1960 and (not to mention) its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 eurocents) for each kilo of sulphur.
It then sells it to the petrochemical industry for 10,000 rupees (83 eurocents) each, because this mineral is common in everyday life and is used to make firewood, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite, and even to bleach sugar.
"We usually carry 70 kg, so we get about 46,000 rupees for each trip", explains Anto, who normally runs three routes a day.
He needs three hours to complete each route, but at the end of the day he has collected 138,000 rupees.
What may seem like a miserable wage for such a purely inhumane effort is three times what he would earn from field work.
"The daily wage of miners here, where the coffee harvest pays 15,000 rupees a day and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros), is very high", explains the carrier, who previously worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees a day, and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a nearby village, for a reason as important as sulfur in Indonesia: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her to Java to convert her to Islam".
Anto has asthma, difficulty breathing, frequent coughing and irritated eyes from the toxic gases.
For three years, 27-year-old Anto has been risking his life at Kawah Ijen, where sulfur has already left its first traces, although he covers his face with a mask and special glasses.
Anto has asthma, difficulty breathing, frequent coughing and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases from the volcano.
This is the price he must pay to achieve his dream.
"I'll work here for two more years because I want to open a shop or learn Spanish or French", he promises in more than just acceptable English.
This kind and intelligent, but life-threatening young man could be working as a tour guide, a waiter, or a hotel receptionist, but instead he does the work of a traitor.
He shares a dirty wooden hut with other people and wakes up at two o'clock every morning because the sulfur also flows out at night, where its characteristic yellow color shines blue in the dark.
Challenging the shadows, he climbs into the crater in the light of a small headlamp on his helmet, which he bought with his own money.
About 400 carriers load the baskets of sulfur on their shoulders at the crater floor.
Despite its large profits, the mining company has not mechanised sulphur extraction to save costs and does not supply any equipment to the operators who work on their own account and are paid by weight.
They also do not receive a share of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) bonus per camera, which the guards of this nature park charge, along with the 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) entrance fee, to tourists who come to photograph the volcano and the human tragedy.
"This work is for the animals, not for the people", protested Madrusin, a tribal, 42-year-old carrier who has been working at the Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
He can carry up to 110 kg and assures that he will continue "as long as possible" because he needs the money to raise his three children between the ages of 10 and 18.
I'm not retiring, I'm dying here because the volcano was my whole life.
Even when the sulfur burns their throats and their eyes itch, when the wind suddenly turns and the miners are crammed into the thick columns that rise from the crater, the men are so tough that no one complains about serious illnesses... except, of course, the usual breathing problems, osteoarthritis, pain in the knees and blisters on the shoulders that have become deformed by the weight of the baskets.
With the basket on his back, Unainik, at 53, can only carry 50 kg.
Every day, he and his companions break 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which is transported by three trucks over a goat trail between the bushes to the camp at Tamansari, 18 kilometers away.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life", Unainik explains, opening his mouth wide, missing some teeth.
Of his five children, the oldest, aged 30, also works as a sulphur-bearer.
Time passes, but poverty persists generation after generation in one of the toughest professions in the world: that of those who work as human burdens on the cawah-en.
Singapore needs babies to save the economy
Singaporeans blame the lack of children on their careers, the stress and the cost of real estate and parenting.
"The population of Singapore must grow".
I am a patriot husband, you are my patriot wife, let us fulfill our civic duty and create life!
It seems incredible that the verses are part of a commercial for mint candy, but nevertheless - or precisely because of that - they went viral on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
The phrases are part of a rapper song that uses local proverbs like, "Shutting a bao in the oven to make fun of the low birth rate in Singapore.
The advertising company BBH, which made the video, hopes that the commercial will come out in a fun way to raise awareness of the problem.
Its creative director, Douglas Hamilton, says he wanted to use the power of music to get people to do their "national duty".
This is something for the Internet, so we had to make it fun and funny.
It is the biggest problem in this country.
We're the worst breeders in the world, so we realized this was a topic we had to deal with.
We knew the government had tried a lot, like marketing perfume with pheromones or organizing speed dating nights.
Many of these ideas may have been creative, but they didn't necessarily lead to success.
So we thought, why don't we do something as creative as possible to address this problem, like compose a rap?
Children 1.2
The government of Singapore is the one who is not taking this issue lightly.
Every year, she spends $1,300 on political initiatives to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for couples and parents provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave, and distributes tax benefits.
But everything has been very unsuccessful.
Singapore is a wealthy, high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its rulers and its strict social controls.
According to its national population agency, the birth rate is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time this rate was above 2 - also known as the replacement rate - was in 1976.
So why don't the Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of the National Population Agency's marriage and family policy, says this is due to "better education" and "greater career opportunities".
"This has allowed people to have more options and priorities in life than to marry and have a family", she explains.
These changes in social conditions have contributed to the increase in single people and the delay in marriage and births, resulting in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, immigration policies aimed at a drastic increase in immigration to counteract population decline have led to resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites where the hardly-closed xenophobia against many new immigrants is flourishing, especially against the Chinese who are being criticized for keeping wages low and not integrating.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why the ruling party in Singapore scored its worst election result since independence last year.
Since the elections, an attempt has been made to correct the problem of higher contributions and taxes for foreign workers.
Unforeseen Consequences
While the falling birth rate has known effects on a nation's economic growth, tax revenues, healthcare costs and immigration policies, the example of Singapore also shows unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to make sure that not so many small dwellings are built.
It already has an impact on the housing market.
The Urban Development Authority has begun to control the number of small apartments known as "shoe boxes" that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have a living area of 46 square meters and show a great sales success.
However, there is concern that they may promote the lifestyle of the single person and that they may deter construction firms from building large homes for families.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of real estate company EL Developers, says that his "shoe boxes" sell much faster than larger residential units.
They're so popular, and the units sell out days and even weeks faster than the larger housing units.
This makes them much better for our cash flow.
However, he admits that the new standards provide clearer guidance for developers who have previously been hindered by obstacles when they want to build too many small housing units within a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city-state.
Even if these new rules could pave the way for a rise in the national birth rate, the discussions with Singaporeans working in the financial district are to be seen as having little impact.
"People are under a lot of stress, housing and education are expensive, and many people are pushing it out", says one young manager.
The kids can get others.
"It is important to me to have my own money and time", says another man in his early twenties.
Men and women are putting their careers, stress and the cost of ownership and upbringing as reasons why they can't have children.
That's why Singaporeans have the final say when it comes to having children - there's so much the government can do.
