The UNASUR Summit concluded without publication of the Lima Declaration
The sixth summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the publication of the Lima Declaration, which was announced in advance and was to be signed theoretically by the seven Governments present.
Efe repeatedly sought access to the document signed at the VI Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of the Unasur.
When asked about the text, they stated that the content was presented by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, in brief statements to the press.
The access of journalists to information on the summit was limited at all times.
During the day, only the image of the presidential meeting was transmitted in the press room without sound, with the message "private meeting, limited audio".
The few information circulated among the journalists was received by the press officers of some of the governments of Unasur present at the meeting, but not by the Peruvian press officer.
The only document that was circulated during the day was the list of participating presidents, which caused discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more information.
The President of Peru then sent an email to the media with the "concluding statement" of the summit, but it was Humala's statement and not the official document concluding the summit.
Last October Peru hosted the third summit of the South American-Arab States (ASPA), and even on this occasion, despite press urges, the so-called Lima Declaration, which had been announced earlier, was not published.
The official website of ASPA shows that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed that information systems exist for journalists, but they restricted access to information to a high degree.
The summit also ended with Chile and Peru jointly committing to accept a judgment of the Hague Court of Justice settling a border dispute between the two countries.
The Presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the ICC, which begins on Monday in The Hague, in the process initiated by Lima v. Santiago to hear the pleadings of both sides.
"We will follow and implement the judgment on the differences we are currently bringing before this International Court of Justice", Humala said, along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and will remain a country that adheres to international law, seeks peaceful settlements of disputes, concludes agreements and submits to international courts", Piñera adds, and greets Humala with a handshake in front of both countries' flags.
The confirmation by both Presidents that they would submit to the ICC came after Colombia, following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua which it considered a grave error, had filed an action against the Bogotá Convention, which agreed to submit to the judgments of that International Court of Justice.
The summit was attended by the Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from the Unasur since 2011 after the ouster of its President Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host President Ollanta Humala opened the talks in the morning and concluded the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The President read the final document, which stated that 16 decisions had been taken and the lines of action for 31 projects between the South American countries had been set for a total investment of 17 billion dollars.
He said that the Unasur countries would "take significant steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, to which we are extending residence rights decisions".
He said that measures would be taken to "improve cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and organised crime across countries, as well as measures to improve access to medicines and low-cost Internet access in all areas of South America and to act together and efficiently in the event of natural disasters".
With the crisis in Europe, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not take triumphant forms, but serve to expand our production capacity and to show our peoples a better future", Humala added.
"We have decided to prioritise a series of 31 emblematic projects aimed at improving spatial connections in South America, especially in rural and border areas... and thus unite our countries and open up new economic forms", the Peruvian President said in a statement read out.
The project also included five Peruvian ones located on the crossroads of his territory from the coast to Brazil, two of which are to provide better connections with Ecuador, although he gave no further details.
The final document also dealt with the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to re-enter the Union of South American Nations", which is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain an integrated region of prosperity and peace and good neighbourly relations was another aspect emphasized at the summit.
In this regard, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before he began his participation in the regional meeting that he expected a meeting with his counterpart from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico to treat the maritime conflict with respect after a judgment of the ICC challenged by Bogotá.
"Maybe I will meet with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow (Saturday)", Santos said.
"We will review all these routes - they are not exclusive, and the agreement with Nicaragua also makes talks with Nicaragua necessary", he stressed.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will treat this matter as civilized and respectfully as possible", Santos added.
Santos and Ortega are due to meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they intend to attend the inauguration of the country's new president, Enrique Peña Nieto.
As part of the Summit, the Defence Ministers of the bloc also met in advance to adopt the Action Plan for 2013 to strengthen dialogue and consensus on defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter country is currently excluded.
Peru holds the provisional presidency of the regional bloc.
