And if Britain grants this release tomorrow, I think it's done".
And if Sweden interviewed Mr Assange at the Ecuadorian embassy in London or via Skype, as Swedish jurisprudence allows and was done in other cases, the problem was solved.
Correa took the opportunity to establish himself as a defender of press freedom, saying that what he does not tolerate "are mediocrity, evil intent and lies that undermine free expression".
"The greatest enemies of press freedom are not the wicked and perverse politicians, but bad journalists who seek to profit and blackmail", he said.
In this sense, he welcomed the fact that Ecuador is no longer ruled by such journalists "nor by bankers or hegemonic and bourgeois countries", and anticipated that if elected again, he would "deepen the revolution to continue in this right direction".
Correa also supported the decision to maintain the veto against Paraguay in the Unasur until at least his next election, arguing that the body "must remain tough and not allow opportunism and a legally disguised coup" because it "destroyed the legitimacy of democracy in Paraguay".
