At present, this judgment is not being implemented.
It is a problem between a South and a Central American state.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome in the pursuit of a common path.
They need to be treated extensively so that they can be overcome and looked forward.
Likewise, he relied on a good settlement of disputes over the Peru-Chile maritime borders before the same court, saying that "it is right for Latin America to call international courts when both countries commit to accept the judgment, even if it is very harsh".
Regarding the possibility of running for the next presidential election in Ecuador to achieve his third consecutive term, he said he sees this possibility "with great optimism and joy, although sometimes it is also very difficult".
Correa assured that if he loses the February 2013 election, he would withdraw from political life.
I have never been personally interested in power, but under unjust circumstances like those in Ecuador, this socioeconomic poverty can only be corrected by political power.
"My political movement believed that I was the one who guaranteed this likely victory, so I have to fulfill that responsibility", he said.
If I win, it's my last term as president, and then I'll retire from public life.
This is true even if we lose.
"That's decided", he explained.
Mr Correa also referred to the treatment of the health problems of the President of Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, in Cuba.
I just spoke to the vice president of Venezuela, Nicolás Maduro, and he told me that he had traveled there for scheduled, routine treatment and that he would be expected to be able to travel back to Cuba after the election campaign.
"It does not mean a decline in the health of President Chávez", he commented.
The Ecuadorian President took part today in the 6th Summit of Heads of State or Government of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) in Lima, which ended with the call for greater regional integration to ensure sustainable progress, equality and security.
The cause of AIDS deaths today is too late to be identified
Fabrizio was 21 when he was confirmed HIV positive.
"It was like a bomb hit", he says of the moment he received the diagnosis, which the doctor tried to "weaken without noticeable success".
He hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness on his own and began to learn about it, and this with such commitment that he was just celebrating his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), where he joined after several struggles in 1994.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, which was hard to imagine in the early 1990s when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigma.
At that time, even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye "because it led to a dead end".
AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome with quality of life.
However, many people still come to the clinic who know nothing about their illness and who have already been damaged by the virus and whose immune system has been depleted and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the world's first reported cases of AIDS, "the great success today means that the survival of a patient who is taking treatment in time and the survival of the general population are exactly the same", said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HCG's HIV unit, adding that this information was backed up by a reputable scientific publication in April of this year.
Infectious diseases and HIV/AIDS expert Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that while AIDS is not a death sentence, years of survival and quality of life depend on the degree to which people's immune systems are impaired at the start of treatment, and that those who are not drug-dependent have a higher chance of being: up to 30 years at a count of 200 CD4s and 50 years at a count of 500 CD4.
Simply put, the above statements mean that those diagnosed HIV positive at age 25 can "go straight to age 75 as long as they are under control", explained this expert.
To properly rank this progress, it must be remembered that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Even though mortality has declined significantly in recent years (in Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS has decreased from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UNICEF's annual report), it is true that 60 percent of the patients listed in the national database have died since the onset of AIDS.
In 2011 alone, 255 people died in Jalisco, and as of May this year, there have been 187 deaths; however, it is assured that since 2005 there has been universal access to antiretroviral medicines.
- So why are people still dying from it?
- I don't think the problem is access to treatment.
This is my opinion, and so is our hospital.
At least in the last 12 years, we haven't had any problems with the supply of the drugs. The problem is that people get in a far advanced state because they don't know their infection status, which is very late in the disease.
He makes a striking statement: "Nine out of ten patients come to us when they already have an accompanying infection, and to influence global mortality, early diagnosis is needed, so massive screening tests must be offered to all those who need it".
This proposal is supported by experts and officials of the Consejo Estatal de Prevención del Sida en Jalisco (Coesida) (the State AIDS Prevention Committee in Jalisco) and by patients such as Fabrizio, who had his test done in a private laboratory, for the sole reason that it had been done by a friend of his who, despite his young age, was already in the AIDS phase and even had Kaposi sarcoma (a cancerous tumor), one of the common complications.
Everything is different when you know you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die and they don't want to hear anything.
"If I have to die, I'd rather blow three times", they say in my case.
The change was for improvement, I eat well, I exercise, and I take my medication.
Today, all his parents know is that he had cancer.
I live a normal life, like everyone else.
"I work, I do a lot of things, I have an active but responsible sex life, I take care of my health and that of the other person", says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimate details with MILENIO JALISCO in order to use his testimony to animate those who are afraid as part of the global AIDS Day.
They should get tested if they're in the risk group, and the sooner they know they're HIV positive, the better, and once they've got the diagnosis, they should learn how to live responsibly, like all people.
His message is a summary of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There are huge gaps between health programs and the common citizen, explains Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has taken up the HIV issue.
And the most important thing is prevention.
In the places designated for this purpose, "the distribution of condoms was actually increased; they were previously given individually, now they give us packages of a hundred pieces, which is good, but there are still people who do not have access to a condom", he said.
Young people are at risk of new infections.
"What do you need these for?" is a common mockery of social workers, school counselors, pharmacy and health care workers who do not want to expose young people, the correspondent assured.
He proposed reorientating this inefficient distribution, not only by placing condoms behind the counter but in the delivery machines in public toilets of facilities frequented by young people.
It is not intended to promote promiscuity.
They are not to be paid for the beer and motel, as Governor Emilio González answered the question of whether preservatives would be distributed under his administration.
"Sexuality is not like that; it's best to bring the condoms closer to those who are already engaged in sexual activity", he said.
Key data from Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
The state is ranked fourth in the nation in new and cumulative AIDS cases, and 13th in HIV.
92% of infections occur through sexual intercourse, 6% through blood and 2% perinatally.
It's estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV because for every recorded case, there are four or five people who don't know.
The United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit upheld a judgment not recognizing the restructuring of the Vitro Group's liabilities achieved through a trade competition in Mexico, setting a disastrous precedent for any national company with branches in a neighbouring country that has payment problems.
So you could say that the survival procedures that Mexican laws allow for companies are not valid in the land of stars and stripes, contrary to international agreements.
In practice, the recognition of the judgment by Judge Harlin Hale on June 15 in the Bancarrotas District Court for the Northern District of Texas leaves Mexican companies vulnerable to the seizure of their property beyond the Bravo River.
However, the ruling opens doors for the largest glass manufacturer in Mexico to appeal three cases to the United States Supreme Court.
While the judge in the case points out that creditors must be subject to the bankruptcy laws of the United States, the New Orleans-based Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals first says that the main case involves the Mexican-based trade competition.
The first point would mean that international cooperation in insolvency proceedings by companies with a cross-border profile is not known.
