The seriousness of the case is that the Court set aside a document sent by the Government of Mexico under the Figura amicus curiae (Friend of the Court) describing the proceedings conducted by Vitro under the Trade Competition Act and pointing out that it had strictly complied with the agreements signed by the two countries in order to comply with Chapter 15 of the United States Bankruptcy Code.
It is also noted that the country has submitted to the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the established rules for cross-border insolvency cases that guarantee equality between debtors and creditors.
