Starting the course studying "The End of the World"
Each week, students study apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
Every semester, when the professor of religion decided to take a course on the end of the world, he knew he had an irresistible fishhook: the end of the "long countdown" of the Mayan calendar on December 21, which many people believed meant the end of the world.
But Charmé had no idea what to expect in the next two months: the devastating Hurricane Sandy, which some have called "Deudarmageddon", and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place Christian theorists believe the apocalypse begins.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever", Charmé told students at Rutgers University in Camden, New Jersey, this week.
If anyone analyzes what has happened in the world today as if we were thirty days away from it, this would be a really good period.
And he reminds us that bad is good for those with an apocalyptic mentality.
And he's not the only professor who's offering classes on the "end of the world" this semester, which is supposed to be the last in history.
At Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker is teaching a course on media, culture and the end of the world.
Each week, students study apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
"We analyze why these ideas spread over time", he said, as well as the way hypothetical scenarios are offered that lead to a particular human behavior.
If nuclear material gets into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, the students analyzed movies with apocalyptic content and examined how they compare to real life.
"I've tried to inform the students about what's possible, likely, credible and impossible", Vacker said.
On the main campus of the University of Pennsylvania, Professor of Latin American History Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of art history and anthropology, have teamed up to offer a course simply titled "The End of the World".
"We're not taking 2012 so we can always keep the option of re-starting the course in case the world doesn't end", Restall said.
Despite the "previous collapse", students must study, create projects and take final exams.
Penn State is taking the final exam on the eve of the apocalypse, so students have no choice but to "work until the night when the world is supposedly coming to an end", Restall said.
The courses were very popular.
"In two hours there were no more places", Restall said of his high-average student course, which was filled with 35 students.
For weeks before the start of the semester, we received e-mails from students asking if there were still seats available.
The students, for their part, assure us that the course is one of the most interesting.
"It's fascinating to see what people do to comfort themselves", said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student at Rutgers-Camden School of Religion and Sociology in Haddonfield, New Jersey.
The apocalyptic sectarian or religious mentality is really just a matter of comfort or lack thereof.
The 25-year-old psychology and nursing student Will Wekesa says he's seen all the apocalyptic movies.
"I have never heard of a class where this is taught", he said.
I'm enjoying it.
But none of the students interviewed - let alone a professor - declared belief in the deadline of December 21.
"Our first project was about the Mayan prophecy, and in a certain way we discredit it", said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old West Chester Temple senior.
The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it is just a key point in the calendar, Restall said.
He notes, however, that there is an apocalyptic fear in Western society that dates back several centuries when people responded to changes in their environment with predictions of the end of the world.
The Internet has increased these speculations.
"Otherwhere people don't think that way", he says.
This is especially the case in the English-speaking world.
